9. DISCLOSURE AND NON-DISCLOSURE OBLIGATIONS

9.1 Confidential Information Defined. For the purposes of this Agreement, "Confidential Information" refers to all details pertaining to the subject matter of this contract that have been identified as confidential, trade secret or proprietary by the disclosing Party (either in writing or verbally), and which are not publicly available. If such information is shared orally, it must be summarized in writing within thirty (30) days following the disclosure. However, "Confidential Information" does not encompass any data that the receiving Party can demonstrate:

  a) was already legally accessible to the public without violating this Agreement by the receiving Party;
  b) was known to or obtained by the receiving Party lawfully prior to receipt from the disclosing Party, and without an obligation of confidentiality;
  c) was independently developed or acquired by the receiving Party without any reference to such information, as verified by appropriate documentation.

In this revised version, the emphasis has shifted slightly towards the receiver of the confidential information, making it clear that they have a responsibility to demonstrate that the information falls under one of the exceptions, rather than the disclosing party having to prove otherwise. This subtly changes the onus of proof and may potentially provide more protection for the receiving party.
